\begin{frame}{Variance}
\protect\hypertarget{variance}{}
\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  Let \(g\left(X\right) = \left(X - \mu\right)^2\) for a discrete random
  variable, \(X\), with expectation \(\mu\):
  \[\mathbb{E}g\left(X\right) = \sum_{x\in\Omega}\left(x - \mu\right)^2\times\Pr\left(x\right) = \sigma^2 \geq 0\]
\end{itemize}

is the VARIANCE of \(X\) but the EXPECTATION of the random variable
\(g\). Since \(\left(X-\mu\right)^{2} = X^2 - 2X\mu + \mu^2\), we can
rewrite the variance of \(X\) as
\[\sigma^2 = \sum_{x\in\Omega}\left(x^2 - 2x\mu + \mu^2\right)\times\Pr\left(x\right) \\
= \sum_{x\in\Omega}x^2 \times \Pr\left(x\right) - 2\mu\sum_{x\in\Omega}x \times \Pr\left(x\right) +
  \mu^2 \sum_{x\in\Omega} \Pr\left(x\right) \\
= \mathbb{E}\left[X^2\right] - 2\mu^2 + \mu^2 = \mathbb{E}\left[X^2\right] - \mu^2\]
- \(\sigma = \sqrt[+]{\sigma^{2}}\) is the STANDARD DEVIATION of \(X\)
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Covariance and Correlation between Two RVs}
\protect\hypertarget{covariance-and-correlation-between-two-rvs}{}
\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  If \(g\left(X,Y\right)=\left(X-\mu_X\right)\left(Y-\mu_Y\right)\),
  COVARIANCE of \(X\) and \(Y\) is defined as
  \[\mathbb{E}g\left(X,Y\right) = 
  \sum_{x\in\Omega_X}\sum_{y\in\Omega_Y}\left(x - \mu_X\right)\left(y - \mu_Y\right)\Pr\left(x \bigcap y\right)
  = \mathbb{E}\left[XY\right] - \mu_X \mu_Y\]
\item
  If
  \(g\left(X,Y\right)=\frac{X-\mu_X}{\sigma_X}\times\frac{Y-\mu_Y}{\sigma_Y}\),
  CORRELATION of \(X\) and \(Y\) is defined as
  \[\mathbb{E}g\left(X,Y\right) =
  \sum_{x\in\Omega_X}\sum_{y\in\Omega_Y}\frac{x - \mu_X}{\sigma_X}
  \frac{y - \mu_Y}{\sigma_Y}\Pr\left(x \bigcap y\right) =\\
  \frac{1}{\sigma_X \sigma_Y}
  \sum_{x\in\Omega_X}\sum_{y\in\Omega_Y}\left(x - \mu_X\right)\left(y - \mu_Y\right)
  \Pr\left(x \bigcap y\right) =
  \frac{\mathrm{Cov}\left(X,Y\right)}{\sigma_X \sigma_Y} = \rho\]
\item
  Covariance and correlation measure linear dependence (only). The
  correlation is unit-free and \(-1 \leq \rho \leq 1\), but is
  \(\rho\gtreqqless0\) for two rolls in bowling?
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Bernoulli Distribution}
\protect\hypertarget{bernoulli-distribution}{}
\begin{itemize}[<+->]
\tightlist
\item
  The Bernoulli distribution over \(\Omega=\left\{ 0,1\right\}\) depends
  on a possibly unknown probability parameter
  \(\pi \in \left[0,1\right]\) (not \(3.14159\dots\))
\item
  The probability that \(x = 1\) (``success'') is \(\pi\) and the
  probability that \(x = 0\) (``failure'') is \(1 - \pi\)
\item
  Can write as a Probability Mass Function (PMF)
  \(\Pr\left(x \mid \pi\right)=\pi^{x}\left(1-\pi\right)^{1-x}\)
\item
  What is the expectation of \(X\)?
\item
  What is the variance of \(X\)?
\item
  You could write a model where \(\pi\) is a function of predictors for
  each observation, as in
  \(\pi\left(z\right) = \frac{1}{1+e^{-\alpha - \beta z}}\) for a logit
  model with predictor \(z\) and then estimate the intercept,
  \(\alpha\), and slope, \(\beta\), using Bayes' Rule (in Week04)
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Binomial Distribution}
\protect\hypertarget{binomial-distribution}{}
\begin{itemize}[<+->]
\tightlist
\item
  A Binomial random variable can be defined as the sum of \(n\)
  INDEPENDENT Bernoulli random variables all with the same \(\pi\). What
  is \(\Omega\) in this case?
\item
  What is an expression for the expectation of a Binomial random
  variable?
\item
  What is an expression for the variance of a Binomial random variable?
\item
  What is an expression for \(\Pr\left(x \mid \pi,n=3\right)\)? Hint: 8
  cases to consider
\item
  All succeed, \(\pi^3\) or all fail, \(\left(1 - \pi\right)^3\)
\item
  1 succeeds and 2 fail \(\pi^1 \left(1-\pi\right)^{3 - 1}\) but there
  are 3 ways that could happen
\item
  2 succeed and 1 fails \(\pi^2 \left(1-\pi\right)^{3 - 2}\) but there
  are 3 ways that could happen
\item
  In general,
  \(\Pr\left(x \mid n,\pi\right)={n \choose x}\pi^{x} \left(1-\pi\right)^{n-x} = \frac{n!}{\left(n - x\right)!x!} \pi^{x} \left(1-\pi\right)^{n-x}\)
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Back to Bowling Questions}
\protect\hypertarget{back-to-bowling-questions}{}
\begin{itemize}[<+->]
\tightlist
\item
  Why is the binomial distribution with \(n = 10\) inappropriate for the
  first roll of a frame of bowling?
\item
  Could the Bernoulli distribution be used for success in getting a
  strike?
\item
  Could the Bernoulli distribution be used for the probability of
  knocking over the frontmost pin?
\item
  If \(X_i = \mathbb{I}\{\mbox{pin i is knocked down}\}\) and \(\pi_i\)
  is the probability in the \(i\)-th Bernoulli distribution, which could
  be a function of other pins, what conceptually is
  \[\Pr\left(x_1 \mid \pi_1\right)\prod_{i=2}^{10}
  \Pr\left(x_i \mid \pi_i\left(X_1=x_1,X_2=x_2,\dots,X_{i-1}=x_{i-1}\right)\right)?\]
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Poisson Distribution for Counts}
\protect\hypertarget{poisson-distribution-for-counts}{}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  Let \(n\uparrow \infty\) and let \(\pi \downarrow 0\) such that
  \(\mu = n\pi\) remains fixed and finite. What is the limit of the
  binomial PMF,
  \(\Pr\left(x \mid n,\pi\right)={n \choose x}\pi^{x} \left(1-\pi\right)^{n-x}\)?

  \begin{itemize}[<+->]
  \tightlist
  \item
    \({n \choose x}\pi^{x} = \frac{n!}{x!\left(n - x\right)!} \frac{\mu^x}{n^x} = \frac{n \times \left(n - 1\right) \times \left(n - 2\right) \times \dots \times \left(n - x + 1\right)} {n^x} \frac{\mu^x}{x!} \rightarrow 1 \times \frac{\mu^x}{x!}\)
  \item
    \(\left(1-\pi\right)^{n-x} = \left(1-\frac{\mu}{n}\right)^{n-x} = \left(1-\frac{\mu}{n}\right)^n \times \left(1-\frac{\mu}{n}\right)^{-x} \rightarrow e^{-\mu} \times 1\)
  \item
    Thus, the limiting PMF is
    \(\Pr\left(x \mid \mu\right) = \frac{\mu^xe^{-\mu}}{x!}\), which is
    the PMF of the Poisson distribution over
    \(\Omega = \{0,\mathbb{Z}_+\}\)
  \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\begin{itemize}[<+->]
\tightlist
\item
  What is the variance of a Poisson random variable?
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}[fragile]{Parameterized Bowling Probabilities}
\protect\hypertarget{parameterized-bowling-probabilities}{}
\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  This is a bit artificial because parameters are usually continuous
  (see Week04)
\item
  Let
  \(\Pr\left(x \mid n, \Upsilon\right) = \frac{\log_{n + 2 + \Upsilon}\left(1 + \frac{1}{n + 1 + \Upsilon - x}\right)}{1 - \log_{n + 2 + \Upsilon}\left(1 + \Upsilon\right)}\)
  where \(\Upsilon \in \{0,\mathbb{Z}_+\}\) is a parameter
\end{itemize}

\begin{frame}[fragile]{Joint Probability of \(\Upsilon\) and \(X_1\)}
\protect\hypertarget{joint-probability-of-upsilon-and-x_1}{}
\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  If you going to collect a realization of the first roll of a frame of
  bowling, what is
  \(\Pr\left(\Upsilon \bigcap x_1 \mid \mu, n = 10\right)\) under a

\end{itemize}

\begin{frame}{Takeaways from Homework 1}
\protect\hypertarget{takeaways-from-homework-1}{}
\begin{itemize}
\item
  Probability requires discipline and concentration
\item
  Poker simultaneously combines three perspectives on probability

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Naive: All non-visible cards have equal probability
  \item
    Bayesian: A hand is a sequence of decisions
  \item
    Frequentist: Evaluate a strategy / player over thousands of hands
  \end{itemize}
\item
  And poker illustrates game theory where players have mixed strategies,
  where they randomly make one decision with probability \(\pi\) and
  another decision with probability \(1 - \pi\) in the exact same
  situation
\item
  What would Fisher say about Selbst's last decision to call?
\item
  Knowing either that my last name is Goodrich or that I live in
  Manhattan is sufficient to make it more likely that I am white than
  any other race, but combined the probability is even higher
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}
